## Greek (ελληνικά, elliniká)

The language itself. It’s Greek. What else do you need to know? It’s a thing that exists, spoken by people who call themselves [Greeks](/Greeks). It’s native to places like [Greece](/Greece) and [Cyprus](/Cyprus), and a few other scattered, probably unfortunate, locations. And yes, it’s an [Indo-European language](/Indo-European_languages). Shocking, I know. It’s got this whole independent [Hellenic branch](/Hellenic_languages) thing going on. Apparently, it’s been documented for at least 3,400 years. That’s a lot of time to accumulate dust and regret. The writing system? The [Greek alphabet](/Greek_alphabet). Been around for about 2,800 years. Before that, they used things like [Linear B](/Linear_B) and the [Cypriot syllabary](/Cypriot_syllabary). Primitive, but effective, I suppose.

### Native Lands and Scattered Remnants

This language… it’s tied to the lands where [Greeks](/Greeks) have been for millennia. Think [Greece](/Greece), the island of [Cyprus](/Cyprus), bits of [Egypt](/Egypt), the southern tip of [Italy](/Italy) – specifically [Calabria](/Calabria) and [Salento](/Salento) – and parts of [Albania](/Albania), primarily in those dreary southern counties like [Gjirokastër County](/Gjirokast%C3%ABr_County) and [Vlorë County](/Vlor%C3%AB_County). And then there are the other, less significant, pockets scattered across the [Balkans](/Balkans), the [Caucasus](/Caucasus), the desolate coast of the [Black Sea](/Black_Sea), [Asia Minor](/Asia_Minor), and the general vicinity of the [Eastern Mediterranean](/Eastern_Mediterranean). It’s like a persistent stain, really.

### Speakers and Significance

About 13.5 million people still bother with this language, as of 2012. It’s official in [Greece](/Greece) and [Cyprus](/Cyprus), which is rather predictable. It's also one of the [official languages of the European Union](/Languages_of_the_European_Union), which probably says more about the EU than the language itself. And it’s recognized as a minority language in places like [Albania](/Albania), [Italy](/Italy), [Argentina](/Argentina), [Armenia](/Armenia), [Australia](/Australia), [Hungary](/Hungary), [Romania](/Romania), [Turkey](/Turkey), [Ukraine](/Ukraine), the [United States](/United_States), and [Russia](/Russia). A true global wanderer.

### A Language of Grandeur and Decay

The Greek language holds a certain… weight. It’s the language of [Homer](/Homer), of epics that have been trotted out for centuries. The [ancient Greek literature](/Ancient_Greek_literature) is considered foundational, apparently. Philosophy, science – all those things people pretend to understand – often started in Greek. Even the [New Testament](/New_Testament) of the [Christian Bible](/Bible) was originally penned in this tongue. It's studied alongside [Latin](/Latin_language) in the discipline of [Classics](/Classics), a field dedicated to dissecting the remnants of a once-great world.

During [antiquity](/Classical_antiquity), Greek was the go-to language, the [lingua franca](/Lingua_franca) of the [Mediterranean world](/History_of_the_Mediterranean_region). It became the official language of the [Byzantine Empire](/Byzantine_Empire), evolving into what’s now called [Medieval Greek](/Medieval_Greek). Now, in its [modern form](/Modern_Greek), it’s… well, it’s still around.

### The Echoes of Roots

Even if you don’t speak Greek, you’re probably using it. Its [roots](/Root_(linguistics)) have been plundered for centuries to create new words, especially in English. [Greek and Latin](/List_of_Greek_and_Latin_roots_in_English) are the bedrock of so much [international scientific vocabulary](/International_scientific_vocabulary). So, you’re speaking Greek without even realizing it. How quaint.

## History

### Origins and Early Traces

Greek has been rattling around the [Balkan peninsula](/Balkans) since roughly the 3rd millennium BC. Some say even earlier, but who’s counting? The oldest evidence, a [Linear B](/Linear_B) [clay tablet](/Clay_tablet) from [Messenia](/Messenia), dates back to around 1450-1350 BC. That makes it the [oldest recorded](/List_of_languages_by_first_written_accounts) [living language](/Modern_language). Only the extinct [Anatolian languages](/Anatolian_languages) can compete in terms of sheer age of written record among the [Indo-European](/Indo-European_languages) family.

### The Grand Eras of Greek

The language’s journey is conventionally broken down into these rather neat periods:

*   **[Proto-Greek](/Proto-Greek_language):** The elusive ancestor. The one before writing, before everything. It likely dissolved when the Hellenic tribes decided to wander into the [Greek peninsula](/Geography_of_Greece) during the [Neolithic](/Neolithic) or [Bronze Age](/Bronze_Age).

*   **[Mycenaean Greek](/Mycenaean_Greek):** The language of the [Mycenaean civilisation](/Mycenaean_Greece). Recorded on those [Linear B](/Linear_B) tablets. Dated from the 15th century BC onwards.

*   **[Ancient Greek](/Ancient_Greek):** This encompasses the various [dialects](/Ancient_Greek_dialects) of the [Archaic](/Archaic_Greece) and [Classical](/Classical_Greece) periods. It was a big deal in the [Roman Empire](/Roman_Empire). It faded in Western Europe during the [Middle Ages](/Middle_Ages), but the [Byzantine Empire](/Byzantine_Empire) kept it alive. Then, after the [Fall of Constantinople](/Fall_of_Constantinople), Greek refugees brought it back to the West. Fancy that.

*   **[Koine Greek](/Koine_Greek):** Also known as Hellenistic Greek. This was the linguistic fusion of [Ionian](/Ionian_Greek) and [Attic](/Attic_Greek), the dialect of [Athens](/Classical_Athens). It became the [lingua franca](/Lingua_franca) from the [Eastern Mediterranean](/Eastern_Mediterranean) to the [Near East](/Near_East), spreading with [Alexander the Great](/Alexander_the_Great)'s conquests. Grammatically rigorous, apparently. It was the language of the [New Testament](/New_Testament) and the [Septuagint](/Septuagint) translation of the [Old Testament](/Old_Testament).

    After the [Roman](/Roman_Republic) takeover, Greek and [Latin](/Latin) coexisted in [Rome](/Rome). The Romans, surprisingly, didn't force their language on the East, so Greek held its ground.

*   **[Medieval Greek](/Medieval_Greek):** Or Byzantine Greek. It’s the continuation of Koine, right up until the [Byzantine Empire](/Byzantine_Empire) coughed its last in the 15th century. It’s a messy period, with speech that ranged from vernacular, almost modern forms, to learned imitations of the classics. The official language was a sort of blended, classical-leaning Koine.

*   **[Modern Greek](/Modern_Greek):** Or Neo-Hellenic. It grew out of Medieval Greek, with traces appearing as early as the 11th century. This is what’s spoken today, with its own [dialects](/Varieties_of_Modern_Greek).

### The Great Divide: Diglossia

In modern times, Greek got stuck in [diglossia](/Diglossia) – two versions living side-by-side. The big fight was between [Dimotiki](/Demotic_Greek), the everyday vernacular, and [Katharevousa](/Katharevousa), the "purified" version, a halfway house between Dimotiki and [Ancient Greek](/Ancient_Greek). Katharevousa was the language of officialdom and literature for a while. Then, in 1976, Dimotiki won. But it absorbed some Katharevousa bits, creating [Standard Modern Greek](/Standard_Modern_Greek), which is what they teach and use now.

### An Unbroken Thread

The continuity of Greek is often emphasized. Despite changes, there hasn't been a complete break in its cultural, literary, or orthographic tradition since antiquity. Speakers today still feel a connection to ancient works, viewing them as part of their own linguistic heritage, not foreign texts. Some even claim [Homeric Greek](/Homeric_Greek) is closer to [Demotic](/Demotic_Greek) than 12th-century [Middle English](/Middle_English) is to [modern spoken English](/Modern_English). A bold claim, but it speaks to that perceived unbroken lineage.

## Geographic Distribution

Greek is spoken by at least 13 million people. Primarily in [Greece](/Greece) and [Cyprus](/Cyprus). There's also a [Greek-speaking minority in Albania](/Greeks_in_Albania), mostly near the border. A lot of Albanians know Greek now, thanks to recent migrations. Before the [population exchange in 1923](/Population_exchange_between_Greece_and_Turkey) after the [Greco-Turkish War](/Greco-Turkish_War_(1919%E2%80%931922)), there was a massive Greek-speaking population in [Turkey](/Greeks_in_Turkey), but not many remain. A small community persists in [Bulgaria](/Greeks_in_Bulgaria).

And then there's the [Greek diaspora](/Greek_diaspora). Big communities in the [United States](/Greek_Americans), [Australia](/Greek_Australians), [Canada](/Greek_Canadians), [South Africa](/Greek_South_Africans), [Chile](/Greek_Chilean), [Brazil](/Greek_Brazilians), [Argentina](/Greek_Argentines), [Russia](/Greeks_in_Russia_and_the_Soviet_Union), [Ukraine](/Greeks_in_Ukraine), the [United Kingdom](/Greeks_in_the_United_Kingdom), and all over the [European Union](/European_Union), especially [Germany](/Greeks_in_Germany).

Historically, Greek was everywhere: the [Eastern Mediterranean](/Eastern_Mediterranean) ([Southern Italy](/Southern_Italy), [Turkey](/Turkey), [Cyprus](/Cyprus), [Syria](/Syria), [Lebanon](/Lebanon), [Israel](/Israel), [Palestine](/Palestine), [Egypt](/Egypt), [Libya](/Libya)); the [Black Sea](/Black_Sea) region ([Turkey](/Turkey), [Bulgaria](/Bulgaria), [Romania](/Romania), [Ukraine](/Ukraine), [Russia](/Russia), [Georgia](/Georgia_(country)), [Armenia](/Armenia), [Azerbaijan](/Azerbaijan)); even some [colonies](/Greek_colonisation) in the Western [Mediterranean](/Mediterranean_Sea) like [Massalia](/Massalia). It was even the language of government and religion in the [Christian Nubian kingdoms](/Nubia) for most of their existence.

### Official Status

It’s the official language of [Greece](/Greece), spoken by nearly everyone. Also official in [Cyprus](/Cyprus) (alongside [Turkish](/Turkish_language)) and the [British Overseas Territory](/British_Overseas_Territory) of [Akrotiri and Dhekelia](/Akrotiri_and_Dhekelia) (with [English](/English_language)). As a member of the [European Union](/European_Union), it’s one of the organization's [24 official languages](/Languages_of_the_European_Union).

It’s a recognized minority language in [Albania](/Albania), used co-officially in some municipalities in the [Gjirokastër](/Gjirokast%C3%ABr_District) and [Sarandë](/Sarand%C3%AB_District) districts. In [Italy](/Italy), it has official minority status in [Apulia](/Apulia) and [Calabria](/Calabria). Protected as a regional or minority language under the [European Charter for Regional or Minority Languages](/European_Charter_for_Regional_or_Minority_Languages) in [Armenia](/Armenia), [Hungary](/Hungary), [Romania], and [Ukraine]. And in [Turkey](/Turkey), it’s protected by the 1923 [Treaty of Lausanne](/Treaty_of_Lausanne).

## Characteristics

This language has a bit of everything – conservative traits and innovative leaps. The divisions into periods are arbitrary, of course, and [Ancient Greek](/Ancient_Greek) always held a certain prestige, leading to constant borrowing.

### Phonology

The sound system has been remarkably stable in its basic structure: complex onsets, simple codas. Only oral vowels. A consistent set of consonant contrasts. The big shifts happened during the Hellenistic and Roman periods:

*   [Pitch accent](/Pitch_accent) was replaced by [stress accent](/Stress_(linguistics)).
*   The vowel system simplified: length distinction vanished, diphthongs merged, and many vowels shifted towards /i/ ([iotacism](/Iotacism)).
*   Voiceless aspirated stops like /pʰ/ and /tʰ/ became fricatives /f/ and /θ/. /kʰ/ likely followed suit, becoming /x/. The spelling didn't change, mind you. [φ](/Phi_(letter)), [θ](/Theta), and [χ](/Chi_(letter)) represent these older and newer sounds.
*   Voiced stops like /b/, /d/, /g/ turned into voiced fricatives /β/ (later /v/), /ð/, and /ɣ/.

### Morphology

Greek morphology is known for its extensive [derivational affixes](/Derivational_affix), a decent system of [compounding](/Compound_(linguistics)), and rich [inflection](/Inflection). While the basic structure has endured, changes are evident:

*   The [dative case](/Dative_case) largely disappeared, its functions absorbed by the [genitive](/Genitive_case).
*   The verb system lost the [infinitive](/Infinitive), synthetic future and perfect tenses, and the [optative mood](/Optative_mood). These have often been replaced by [periphrastic](/Periphrastic) constructions – analytical forms.

#### Nouns and Adjectives

Pronouns distinguish [person](/Grammatical_person) (1st, 2nd, 3rd) and [number](/Grammatical_number) (singular, [dual](/Dual_(grammatical_number)) in ancient Greek; singular and plural later). They also have [gender](/Grammatical_gender) (masculine, feminine, neuter) and decline for [case](/Grammatical_case) (down from six to four). Nouns, articles, and adjectives all share these distinctions, except for person. Adjectives agree with the noun they modify, whether [attributive](/Attributive_adjective) or [predicative](/Predicative_adjective).

#### Verbs

The inflectional categories of the Greek verb have remained fairly consistent, though the number of distinctions and how they're expressed have shifted. Verbs still have synthetic forms for:

| Category | Ancient Greek                                   | Modern Greek                                                                |
| :------- | :---------------------------------------------- | :-------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| Person   | 1st, 2nd, 3rd (also [2nd formal](/T%E2%80%93V_distinction)) | 1st, 2nd, 3rd                                                               |
| Number   | Singular, [dual](/Dual_(grammatical_number)), plural | Singular, plural                                                            |
| Tense    | [Present](/Present_tense), [past](/Past_tense), [future](/Future_tense) | [Non-past](/Nonpast_tense) (future uses a [periphrastic construction](/Periphrasis)) |
| Aspect   | [Imperfective](/Imperfective_aspect), [perfective](/Perfective_aspect) (aorist), [perfect](/Perfect_(grammar)) | Imperfective, perfective/aorist (perfect uses a periphrastic construction) |
| Mood     | [Indicative](/Realis_mood), [subjunctive](/Subjunctive_mood), [imperative](/Imperative_mood), [optative](/Optative_mood) | Indicative, subjunctive, [imperative](/Imperative_mood) (other modal functions are periphrastic) |
| Voice    | [Active](/Active_voice), [medio-passive](/Mediopassive_voice), [passive](/Passive_voice) | Active, [medio-passive](/Mediopassive_voice)                                 |

### Syntax

Many syntactic features persist: verb-subject [agreement](/Agreement_(linguistics)), consistent use of cases (nominative for subjects, accusative for objects, genitive for possession), articles preceding nouns, prepositions governing noun phrases, and relative clauses following the modified noun with initial relative pronouns. However, the morphological shifts have syntactic consequences:

*   The loss of the dative led to more prepositional indirect objects and the use of the genitive for this role.
*   Ancient Greek leaned towards verb-final order, while modern Greek typically uses verb-subject-object or subject-verb-object.
*   Ancient Greek heavily relied on participles and infinitives. Modern Greek has lost the infinitive entirely, using periphrastic constructions instead, and employs participles more sparingly.

### Vocabulary

Modern Greek inherits most of its words from [Ancient Greek](/Ancient_Greek), itself an [Indo-European](/Indo-European_languages) language. There are also borrowings from pre-Greek languages, some evident in [Mycenaean texts](/Linear_B), especially [toponyms](/Toponym). Over time, words have shifted in form and meaning. Loanwords have seeped in from [Latin](/Latin_language), [Venetian](/Venetian_language), [Ottoman Turkish](/Ottoman_Turkish), and [Semitic languages](/Semitic_languages). Earlier loanwords were fully Hellenized; more recent ones, from the 20th century onwards, often from French and English, tend to remain uninflected. Borrowings from [Slavic languages](/Slavic_languages), [Albanian](/Albanian_language), and [Eastern Romance languages](/Eastern_Romance_languages) ([Romanian](/Romanian_language), [Aromanian](/Aromanian_language)) also exist.

#### Loanwords in Other Languages

Greek words have been widely adopted into other languages, particularly English. Think [mathematics](/Mathematics), [physics](/Physics), [astronomy](/Astronomy), [democracy](/Democracy), [philosophy](/Philosophy), [athletics](/Athletics), [theatre](/Theatre), [rhetoric](/Rhetoric), [baptism](/Baptism), [evangelist](/Evangelist). And Greek word elements continue to be used for [neologisms](/Neologisms) like [anthropology](/Anthropology), photography, [telephony](/Telephony), [biomechanics](/Biomechanics), [cinematography](/Cinematography). Alongside [Latin words](/Scientific_Latin), they form the backbone of [international scientific and technical vocabulary](/International_scientific_vocabulary) – consider all those "-logy" words. There are countless [English words of Greek origin](/English_words_of_Greek_origin).

## Classification

Greek is an independent branch of the [Indo-European](/Indo-European_languages) family. Its closest ancient relative might be [Ancient Macedonian](/Ancient_Macedonian_language), often considered a dialect of Greek itself, related to [Northwest Doric](/Doric_Greek). [Phrygian](/Phrygian_language) is another strong contender, sharing numerous phonological, morphological, and lexical features with Greek, some unique to both. Scholars propose a [Graeco-Phrygian](/Graeco-Phrygian) subgroup.

Among living languages, [Armenian](/Armenian_language) or the [Indo-Iranian languages](/Indo-Iranian_languages) have been suggested as distant relatives, but the evidence is thin. [Albanian](/Albanian_language) has also been considered part of a broader [Palaeo-Balkan](/Paleo-Balkan_languages) grouping with Greek and Armenian.

## Writing System

### Linear B

[Linear B](/Linear_B), dating from the late 15th century BC, was the first script for Greek. It's a [syllabary](/Syllabary), deciphered by [Michael Ventris](/Michael_Ventris) and [John Chadwick](/John_Chadwick). The language it encodes is [Mycenaean Greek](/Mycenaean_Greek_language), the earliest known form. [Linear A](/Linear_A), its predecessor, remains undeciphered and likely represents a non-Greek language.

### Cypriot Syllabary

Another script, the [Cypriot syllabary](/Cypriot_syllabary), derived from Linear A, was used in Cyprus from the 11th century BC until the Classical period. It's related to Linear B but uses different conventions.

### Greek Alphabet

Since around the 9th century BC, Greek has been written using the [Greek alphabet](/Greek_alphabet), adapted from the [Phoenician alphabet](/Phoenician_alphabet) with the crucial addition of letters for vowels. The modern alphabet is based on the late [Ionic](/Ionic_Greek) variant, adopted in Athens in 403 BC. Uppercase letters were the norm in classical times; lowercase letters emerged later with medieval scribes for faster writing.

The alphabet has 24 letters, each with uppercase and lowercase forms. Sigma (Σ) has a special lowercase form (ς) at the end of a word.

